_menu_item','',0),(230,1,'2024-03-15 12:43:21','2024-03-15 05:42:44',' ','','','publish','closed','closed','','230','','','2024-03-15 12:43:21','2024-03-15 05:43:21','',0,'https://healthcaretalent.vn/?p=230',10,'nav_menu_item','',0),(231,1,'2024-03-15 12:43:21','2024-03-15 05:42:44',' ','','','publish','closed','closed','','231','','','2024-03-15 12:43:21','2024-03-15 05:43:21','',0,'https://healthcaretalent.vn/?p=231',11,'nav_menu_item','',0),(232,1,'2024-03-15 12:43:21','2024-03-15 05:42:44',' ','','','publish','closed','closed','','232','','','2024-03-15 12:43:21','2024-03-15 05:43:21','',0,'https://healthcaretalent.vn/?p=232',12,'nav_menu_item','',0),(233,1,'2024-03-15 12:43:21','2024-03-15 05:42:44',' ','','','publish','closed','closed','','233','','','2024-03-15 12:43:21','2024-03-15 05:43:21','',0,'https://healthcaretalent.vn/?p=233',13,'nav_menu_item','',0),(234,1,'2024-03-15 12:43:21','2024-03-15 05:42:44',' ','','','publish','closed','closed','','234','','','2024-03-15 12:43:21','2024-03-15 05:43:21','',0,'https://healthcaretalent.vn/?p=234',14,'nav_menu_item','',0),(235,1,'2024-09-15 14:24:52','2024-09-15 07:24:52','<h2><strong>6 tips to rock your next interview</strong></h2>\r\n<h3>1. Plan your first impression</h3>\r\nWhen up against the open-ended question of “tell me about yourself,” where should you begin? Definitely <em>not</em> at the beginning of your career.\r\n\r\nInterviewers and hiring managers don’t want a recap of your resume. They want to know why you’re the most relevant and interesting person for this job.\r\n\r\nSo give them what they want and answer the question succinctly and directly. Maintain eye contact and remember that you’re in control — you get to decide what parts of your story to emphasize.\r\n<h3>2. Sell your strengths</h3>\r\nIn an interview, talking about your strengths isn’t obnoxious. It’s not bragging or being too forward. In fact, highlighting and sharing your strengths can be one of the most important things to do in a successful interview.\r\n\r\nSo be sure to be prepared to share your strengths in your interview. Take the time to practice how you’d speak about them and find ways to weave them into a discussion of, say, the top three reasons you’d be a great fit for this particular role.\r\n\r\nEven if you’re an introvert or a modest person by nature, there are ways to communicate your strengths without going against your personality.\r\n\r\nFirst, state the facts of what you accomplished:\r\n\r\n<em>Example: “I led a multi-million dollar project that we delivered two weeks ahead of deadline and received amazing feedback from the client.\"</em>\r\n\r\nSecond, highlight what others think about you:\r\n\r\n<em>Example: “In my performance review, I got great feedback from my manager about my ability to mentor junior associates and motivate my team.” </em>\r\n\r\nAnd remember to practice aloud. With just a handful of practice responses beforehand, you can go from stumbling to polished in no time.\r\n<h3>3. Prepare speaking points — not a script</h3>\r\nHow can you be prepared for the interview, but also come across as authentic and spontaneous? The short answer: Bullet points.\r\n\r\nDon’t script responses word for word. Simply capture a few bullet points that communicate the most important points for commonly asked questions.\r\n\r\nSometimes it can feel like you’re at the mercy of the interviewer, says Skillings. “But if you go in feeling comfortable with your speaking points and the things that you want them to remember about you,” she says, “it gives you an opportunity to be strategic and proactive.”\r\n\r\nThis can be especially helpful if there’s an area in your work history that you’re sensitive about, like a gap in your resume. Don’t stick your head in the sand and hope they don’t ask.\r\n\r\nInstead, prepare and practice an answer to a question about that topic so you’ll be in control of your message no matter what the interviewer throws your way.\r\n<h3>4. Show enthusiasm for the role</h3>\r\nIt’s a given that you will research the company and be able to discuss why you’re a good fit for the organization.\r\n\r\nBut even more importantly, you need to express — with sincere enthusiasm! — how you’re a great fit for the job itself and why you’d be excited to do this work. Think about:\r\n<ul>\r\n 	<li>How am I uniquely qualified for this job?</li>\r\n 	<li>Why would I be motivated to succeed if they hired me?</li>\r\n 	<li>How does this job fit into my career goals and what I love to do?</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nHiring managers are trying to get a feel for whether you would be a passionate, strong performer if you’re hired, Skillings notes. So be sure to bring your A-game when it comes to enthusiasm.\r\n<h3>5. Tell a good (short) story</h3>\r\nWhen answering questions about specific projects you led, Skillings says, “you want to have a little bit of a story arc. You want to paint a picture and you want to make sure that you\'re really sharing what you in particular did to contribute to the project.”\r\n\r\nBut how?\r\n<ol>\r\n 	<li><strong>Start with some backstory.</strong> You don’t need to provide all the details, but just enough context to explain why the project was important.</li>\r\n 	<li><strong>Highlight your actions.</strong> Explain what you did, including the obstacles you faced and how you addressed them.</li>\r\n 	<li><strong>End with positive outcomes.</strong> Be sure to highlight why the project and your contributions were important. That can be through a concrete business result (“my contributions helped increase revenue by 8%”) or something more anecdotal (“my leadership helped us come in under budget and the customer renewed their contract”).</li>\r\n</ol>\r\nAnd to make your story concise and engaging, remember the following:\r\n<ul>\r\n 	<li>Keep it under two minutes.</li>\r\n 	<li>Use <em>I</em> instead of <em>we</em>.</li>\r\n 	<li>Think of your story as the start of a dialogue, not a monologue. If the interviewer asks follow-up questions to dig deeper, you know you’ve succeeded.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h3>6. End on a positive note</h3>\r\nThere’s plenty of advice out there that says to end the interview with a question like, “Do you have any concerns about me as a candidate?”\r\n\r\nSkillings thinks that’s a bad idea.\r\n\r\nOne problem is that most interviewers and hiring managers, especially at big companies, are trained not to give feedback like that on the spot. Plus, why end the interview by inviting negativity?\r\n\r\nInstead, try ending on a positive note by asking something like: “What do you think are the most important qualities for someone in this role?”\r\n\r\nIt may open up a final opportunity for you to talk about your experience in a different way to make that final lasting impression.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<p style=\"text-align: right;\">Source: LinkedIn</p>','6 Interview Tips That Can Help You Get Hired','','publish','closed','closed','','five-construction-trends-shaping-the-industry-in-2024','','','2024-10-13 21:17:01','2024-10-13 14:17:01','',0,'https://healthcaretalent.vn/?post_type=advice&#038;p=235',0,'advice','',0),(236,1,'2024-03-15 14:25:58','2024-03-15 07:25:58','','Five Construction Trends Shaping the Industry in 2024 .jpg (1)','','inherit','open','closed','','five-construction-trends-shaping-the-industry-in-2024-jpg-1','','','2024-03-15 14:25:58','2024-03-15 07:25:58','',235,'https://healthcaretalent.vn/wp-content/uploads/2024/03/advice/Five-Construction-Trends-Shaping-the-Industry-in-2024-.jpg-1.webp',0,'attachment','image/webp',0),(238,1,'2024-09-15 14:45:20','2024-09-15 07:45:20','<section class=\"mdc-u-grid mdc-u-grid-col-md-12 mck-u-animation-blur-in-400\">\r\n<div class=\"mdc-u-grid-col-md-start-2 mdc-u-grid-col-md-end-12 mdc-u-grid-col-lg-start-3 mdc-u-grid-col-lg-end-11\">\r\n<div class=\"mdc-c-description___SrnQP_79c2a62 mdc-u-ts-5\" data-component=\"mdc-c-description\">\r\n<div class=\"mck-u-links-inline\">\r\n\r\nImagine you\'re in an interview, facing a series of standard questions requiring more than straightforward answers. The pressure is on to make a lasting impression. What if there was a way to answer these questions effectively and captivate your interviewers? The secret lies in storytelling.\r\n\r\nStorytelling in interview responses can transform your experiences into memorable narratives that showcase your skills, solutions, and the impact you made in your previous roles. By mapping your roles to stories, you can effectively highlight your strengths and achievements, making your answers more engaging and helping you stand out to interviewers.\r\n\r\nIn this article, we\'ll explore how to craft compelling stories from your resume and practice delivering them to ensure you can adapt to any question.\r\n<h2>The challenge of making a lasting impression</h2>\r\nJob interviews can be daunting, especially when competing against other qualified candidates. The challenge is to differentiate yourself and leave a lasting impression on your interviewers. Traditional interview responses, which often focus solely on listing duties and responsibilities, need to be revised. Interviewers may struggle to remember your specific contributions or the impact you made in your previous roles. This is where storytelling can make a significant difference.\r\n<h3>Creates engaging and memorable responses</h3>\r\nStorytelling allows you to present your experiences in a way that is engaging and memorable. Instead of merely stating that you led a successful project, you can describe the challenges you faced, the strategies you employed, and the positive outcomes that resulted from your efforts. This narrative approach not only captures attention but also helps interviewers visualise your contributions and the impact you made.\r\n<h3>Highlights key skills and achievements</h3>\r\nWhen you craft stories from your resume, you can strategically highlight key skills and achievements. For example, instead of simply saying you improved a process, you can tell a story about how you identified inefficiencies, collaborated with team members to develop a new approach, and ultimately increased productivity by 20%. This detailed narrative showcases your problem-solving abilities, teamwork, and leadership skills.\r\n<h3>Demonstrates problem-solving and critical thinking</h3>\r\nStorytelling also allows you to demonstrate your problem-solving and critical-thinking skills. By detailing the obstacles you encountered and the steps you took to overcome them, you show interviewers that you can think on your feet and handle complex situations. This is particularly important for roles that require analytical thinking and strategic decision-making.\r\n<h3>Creates a connection with the interviewer</h3>\r\nA well-told story can create a connection with the interviewer. Personal anecdotes, especially those that highlight your values and motivations, can help you build rapport and make a positive impression. Interviewers are more likely to remember candidates who share relatable and compelling stories.\r\n<h2>Practical solutions and strategies</h2>\r\nHere’s how you can get started with incorporating storytelling into your interview responses:\r\n<h3>Identify key experiences</h3>\r\nBegin by identifying key experiences from your resume that demonstrate your skills and achievements. Look for moments when you made a significant impact, overcame challenges, or led successful projects. These experiences will form the foundation of your stories.\r\n<h3>Structure your stories</h3>\r\nA good story has a clear structure: a beginning, a middle, and an end. Start by setting the scene and providing context. Describe the situation or challenge you faced (beginning), explain the actions you took (middle), and conclude with the results or outcomes (end). This structure helps ensure your stories are coherent and easy to follow.\r\n<h3>Use the STAR method</h3>\r\nThe STAR method (Situation, Task, Action, Result) is a popular framework for structuring interview responses. It can be particularly effective for storytelling. Outline the Situation you were in, the Task you needed to accomplish, the Actions you took, and the Results you achieved. This method ensures that your stories are focused and relevant.\r\n<h3>Practice crafting stories</h3>\r\nPractice crafting stories from different parts of your resume. Think about how you can adapt these stories to answer various interview questions. For example, a story about leading a project can be used to demonstrate leadership, problem-solving, and teamwork skills. The more you practice, the more natural your storytelling will become.\r\n<h3>Tailor your stories to the job description</h3>\r\nWhen preparing for an interview, review the job description and identify the key skills and qualifications required for the role. Tailor your stories to highlight these attributes. For example, if the job requires strong project management skills, focus on stories showcasing your successful experience in managing projects.\r\n<h3>Keep it concise</h3>\r\nWhile storytelling is powerful, it is important to keep your responses concise and to the point. Avoid going off on tangents or including unnecessary details. Aim to deliver your stories clearly and concisely, ensuring that each one effectively communicates your skills and achievements.\r\n<h3>Use vivid language</h3>\r\nUse vivid and descriptive language to bring your stories to life. Instead of saying, \"I improved the process,\" say, \"I identified bottlenecks in the workflow, streamlined communication between departments, and implemented a new software tool, resulting in a 20% increase in efficiency.\" Descriptive language helps paint a picture in the interviewer\'s mind.\r\n<h3>Incorporate emotions</h3>\r\nFeel free to incorporate emotions into your stories. Talk about how you felt during the experience — whether it was the satisfaction of overcoming a challenge or the excitement of achieving a goal. Emotions can make your stories more relatable and memorable.\r\n<h3>Practice delivery</h3>\r\nPractice delivering your stories out loud. This will help refine your narrative, ensure a natural flow, and build confidence. Consider practising with a friend or mentor who can provide feedback on your storytelling technique.\r\n<h2>Future trends and considerations</h2>\r\n<h3>The rise of soft skills</h3>\r\nAs the job market evolves, there is an increasing emphasis on soft skills such as communication, empathy, and adaptability. Storytelling is a powerful way to demonstrate these skills during an interview. You can position yourself as a well-rounded candidate by sharing stories that highlight your interpersonal abilities.\r\n<h3>Virtual interviews</h3>\r\nWith the rise of remote work, virtual interviews have become more common. Storytelling can be particularly effective in virtual interviews, where building a connection with the interviewer can be more challenging. A compelling story can help you stand out and leave a lasting impression, even in a virtual setting.\r\n<h3>AI and automated hiring processes</h3>\r\nAs AI and automation become more prevalent in the hiring process, storytelling can help differentiate you from other candidates. While AI can screen for qualifications and experience, storytelling showcases your personality, creativity, and unique experiences — qualities that are difficult for machines to evaluate.\r\n<h3>Continuous learning and adaptation</h3>\r\nThe ability to continuously learn and adapt is crucial in today\'s fast-paced job market. Storytelling allows you to demonstrate your learning agility by sharing examples of how you\'ve adapted to new challenges and acquired new skills. This can be particularly important for roles that require continuous innovation and growth.\r\n<h2>Final thoughts: Storytelling can help you stand out from the crowd</h2>\r\nIn today\'s competitive job market, making a lasting impression in an interview is more crucial than ever. By incorporating storytelling into your interview responses, you can transform your past experiences into compelling narratives that highlight your skills and achievements and engage and captivate your interviewers.\r\n\r\nThis approach goes beyond the traditional methods of answering questions. It allows you to showcase your problem-solving abilities, critical thinking, and personal values memorably. Remember, the key to successful storytelling is preparation and practice. Identify your key experiences, structure your stories effectively, and tailor them to the job you\'re applying for.\r\n\r\nWith these strategies, you can enhance your interview performance, stand out from the competition and ultimately, increase your chances of securing the job. So, start crafting your stories today and take your interview skills to the next level.\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n</section>&nbsp;\r\n<p style=\"text-align: right;\">Source: LinkedIn</p>','Why Storytelling Could Be the Key to Acing Your Next Job Interview','','publish','closed','closed','','what-is-an-exit-interview-and-how-should-you-prepare','','','2024-10-22 18:02:50','2024-10-22 11:02:50','',0,'https://healthcaretalent.vn/?post_type=advice&#038;p=238',0,'advice','',0),(241,1,'2024-03-16 14:48:39','2024-03-16 07:48:39','','Request a Call Back','','publish','closed','closed','','request-a-call-back','','','2024-03-16 14:49:55','2024-03-16 07:49:55','',0,'https://healthcaretalent.vn/?page_id=241',0,'page','',0),(242,1,'2024-03-16 14:48:39','2024-03-16 07:48:39','','Request a Call Back','','inherit','closed','closed','','241-revision-v1','','','2024-03-16 14:48:39','2024-03-16 07:48:39','',241,'https://healthcaretalent.vn/?p=242',0,'revision','',0),(246,1,'2024-03-17 00:07:25','2024-03-16 17:07:25','','logo','','inherit','open','closed','','logo-2','','','2024-03-17 00:07:25','2024-03-16 17:07:25','',0,'https://healthcaretalent.vn/wp-content/uploads/2024/03/logo.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(248,1,'2024-03-17